05006nam a22008175i 9780231543989DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016024793  a97802315439897 a10.7312/luck177022doi  a(DE-B1597)480272  a(OCoLC)979683335  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aD743.42b.L8313 2017 4aD743.42b.L8313 2017 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a940.53/522231 aLucken, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Japanese and the War :bExpectation, Perception, and the Shaping of Memory /cMichael Lucken. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b27 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia Perspectives: History, Society, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Names -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Nation out to Conquer -- t2 A Totalitarian Dynamic, 1940–1945 -- t3 The Meaning of the War -- t4 Heroes and the Dead -- t5 Fear and Destruction -- t6 Postwar Complexities -- t7 The American Occupation, or the Present Versus the Past -- t8 The Plurality of History -- t9 Individual Conscience and Collective Inertia -- t10 Memory and Religion -- t11 From Monument to Museum -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMemories of World War II exert a powerful influence over Japan's culture and society. In The Japanese and the War, Michael Lucken details how World War II manifested in the literature, art, film, funerary practices, and education reform of the time. Concentrating on the years immediately before and after (1937 to 1952), Lucken explores the creation of an idea of Japanese identity that still resonates in everything from soap operas to the response to the Fukushima nuclear disaster.Lucken defines three distinct layers of Japan's memory of World War II: the population's expectations at the beginning, the trauma caused by conflict and defeat, and the politics of memory that arose after Japan lost to the Allied powers. Emphasizing Japanese-language sources, Lucken writes a narrative of the making of Japanese cultural memory that moves away from Western historical modes and perspectives. His approach also paints a new portrait of the U.S. occupation, while still maintaining a cultural focus. Lucken sets out to capture the many ways people engage with war, but particularly the full range of Japan's experiences, which, he argues, the Japanese state has yet to fully confront, leading to a range of tensions at home and abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCollective memoryzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar and societyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zJapanxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aGrimwade, Karen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/luck1770240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231543989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231543989/original  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_